gomodel:SYNGO_4862  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 7: Glycine-induced increase in GluA1 surface expression was absent in cultured neurons prepared from synaptobrevin-2 (VAMP2) knockout mice. Glycine treatment increased the mEPSC amplitude in control cultured neurons but not in cultured neurons lacking synaptobrevin-2, while having no effect on basal mEPSC amplitude. As expected from the presynaptic functions of synpatobrevin-2, the mEPSC frequency was dramatically reduced in the synaptobrevin-2 knockout cultures and was not increased by glycine treatment.\n\nOver-expression of wild-type synaptobrevin-2 rescued both the reduction in basal surface GluA1 levels in cultured synaptobrevin-2 knockout neurons as well as the loss of glycine-induced \"LTP\". Notably, synaptobrevin-2 knockout neurons exhibited an impairment in constitutive TfR recycling, which was rescued by expression of wild-type synaptobrevin-2.\n\nAuthors conclude: \"These findings suggest that synpatobrevin-2 is involved in both the constitutive delivery of AMPARs to the plasma membrane as well as the enhanced regulated delivery of AMPARs during LTP, but is absolutely required only for the latter.\". Experimental description: M&M: \"Dissociated hippocampal cultures were prepared from newborn C57BL/6 mice infected with lentiviruses at DIV 8-9 and processed for experiments 10-11 days later as previously described (Ahmad et al., 2012).\"\n\nFigure 7: \"Sample images and summary graph of glycine-induced changes in surface GluA1 in control and cultured neurons prepared from Syb-2 KO mice.\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2022-09-08" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4862" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

